{
  "text": "bAR signalling through the cAMP system is spatially controlled in a subtype-dependent manner with the b 2 AR signal detected only after stimulation at the T-tubule. These experiments do not tell us whether the b 2 AR itself is absent from the non-tubule sarcolemma, or whether it is present but preferentially coupled to a non-Gs-cAMP pathway. Silencing of the b 2 AR-cAMP signal would suggest a location of the b 2 AR within caveolin/cholesterol-rich domains, where it would associate with Gi or eNOS, and be consistent with increased b 2 AR-cAMP signals seen after disruption with MbCD. However, the evidence places those domains within the T-tubule rather than on the crest of the cardiomyocyte. Clearly, there is a need to establish the nature of the downstream signalling accessed by b 2 AR through Gi-or non-G-protein pathways and its spatial localization. During heart failure the b 2 AR-cAMP signalling is no longer localized to even the remaining T-tubules, and now propagates along the cardiomyocyte in similar way to that produced by the b 1 AR. Is this to partially replace the function of the preferentially lost b 1 ARs? Does it necessarily imply that non-Gs signalling of the b 2 AR is reduced? Does the loss of non-Gs coupling or the increased range of cAMP targets mean that the b 2 AR is now as pro-arrhythmic and pro-apoptotic as the b 1 AR? One point of note is that PKA-dependent phosphorylation of the b 2 AR drives the Gs to Gi switch [CITATION_1] and that a b 2 AR mutant without PKA phosphorylation sites resembled the b 1 AR in its damaging effect on the cardiomyocyte. [CITATION_2] Finally, reverse remodelling of the ventricular myocyte T-tubule system was observed after SERCA2a gene therapy and this was accompanied by a reversal of the Spatial control of bAR system in heart failure de-localization of the b 2 AR. Does this indicate general recovery or is there a more specific link between SERCA2a levels and t-tubular structure or b 2 AR signalling? In general, despite variations between rodent and human, the main components of the b 1 -and b 2 AR systems exist in both species and parallel changes in T-tubule architecture and bAR sensitivity are observed. It is therefore likely that the efforts put in by many groups to unravel the spatial regulation of the bAR system will be relevant for the understanding of human disease.",
